I'll lay out some possible scenarios and some plays you can do and you can look back at this during the day tomorrow and decide what you want to do
Tomorrow there'll be a little calendar icon at the top of the screen where the voting buttons and your role info is - you can click on it and click Day 1 to see this night's text

Okay so here's some options for you
#### OPTION ONE ####
If we are forced to claim due to the village saying all claim you can claim villager

This has the disadvantage that the village may decide to start lynching villager claims. If all the bags add up and there are no duplicate power role claims, then the usual thing to do is deduce wolves are claiming villager and start lynching in that pool. You might end up being the choice of the day - especially if you're coming on late, people tend to have a bias towards voting people who aren't around most of the day and those votes might stick.
However, it's the least risky option for you and if you're not feeling good then there's a decent chance you can make it
#### OPTION TWO ####
If we are forced to claim you can claim Stalker
At this point you can choose one of several options

1) That you stalked a target to the kill - implicating them as a possible killing wolf. Depending on what has been claimed already and what you get from the code on my read you can decide who to frame. If I read Ninety as sleepwalker or villager you could frame them as they won't have much deniability.

It's possible for a sleepwalker to coincidentally also visit the kill but if there are no other conflicts then it's likely that the village will choose to execute them "just in case" because, after all, they are just a villager

The upside of this is you wouldn't have to shift straight away - if they're dug as sleepwalker then you look legit, but anything else is bad and you have to shift away - but thats fine because you're not sure you can pull off a shift later in the game with your time zone

The risk of this is that there is a possibility another, real stalker stalks your claim and contradicts you - then you're in a 50/50 and you'll have to convince the village that the other stalker is a wolf making a play to save a wolf. Which leads us onto stalker option 2)

2) You do this play. Wait for a stalker to give a stalk and either a) say that you stalked their target and they are not telling the truth about where they went (they went to the kill) or b) you stalked the stalker and they didn't go to the person they are claiming to have stalked

The upside to this is if there are not many GD and we can sucessfully kill/shift them then we can implicate two people as possible wolves - the stalker and the target they are trying to mislead us on. If we are able to shut down gravedigger intel entirely then we can even use your time zone to an advantage - pointing out you're not shifted by them because of your time zone

3) you can say you stalked our Direwolf, Goro and they went nowhere. Currently I'm suggesting that Goro claims to have been blocked. If you claim they went nowhere then this verifies that they were blocked. It's also safe if someone else stalked Goro because he really won't have gone anywhere.

Downside to this is it somewhat links you and Goro and if something happens to one of you, the other is probably going down too. Not to mention that some players will have some red flags popping up about this - but I don't think it will be conclusive enough to do anything about - will just add suspicion later
4) You can claim stalker and instead of Goro claiming blocked, you claim to have been blocked.

This is the least risky Stalker play and as long as your claim doesn't take us over the limit for stalkers, you'll be safe from execution for a couple of days. If there are too many stalker claims then this could go either way for you. Some people may see you as less likely to be a wolf as you are the only person claiming blocked, so how can you be a wolf - others will suggest its a wolf play, and they'd be right. Those kind of things are easy for the rest of us to play down though so it's not a huge risk
#### OPTION THREE ####
You claim into bag #2 - the diseased, protector and elder bag.

What often happens in this setup is the village all claim, except for people in that bag - they either claim just being from that bag or they claim two of the three. E.g they'll say "I'm either protector or diseased".

Once there is a conflict - and unless we got very lucky with our kill, there will be a conflict - often they'll make people claim all at once. So they'll wait until all three of you are there and countdown ,3,2,1 and you say your claim at the same time.
You can choose any of them but Elder is probably the best one to make.

The downside to this option is you are almost certainly putting yourself into a conflict. This is a conflict that might end up in your execution tomorrow, which is not ideal. It does however have the advantage of revealing the roles in that bag, which we can then avoid (ifdiseased and elder) or block (if protector). That's very useful. However if you survive the day you're probably going to have to shift away and that then more or less confirms the others as legit.
It's a big play, very risky but if you're able to pull it off it's strong because it outs all of the roles we are worried about.
#### OPTION FOUR ####
It might be that the village don't force us all to claim. If they're not very organised then it might not even happen - in which case you can do one of two things.
i) Do nothing and not claim anything tomorrow, deferring this decision to another day

ii) make one of the above plays, which becomes both riskier because you're doing it somewhat blind but all the more effective because "why would a wolf take this risk" and it seems more likely to be true
Okay those are some options for you
And you can play it by ear tomorrow as to what's happening and which you want to do

Summary:
## Roles in this Setup (for new players) ##

### village aligned: ###

*Villager* - is exactly that, a village aligned role without any night action

*Sleepwalker* - is a villager without night actions, but makes a random visit at night, they don't know they are SW tho

*Stalker* - can follow one player at night and see who they visit

*Gravedigger* - can check a dead players role at night, Note in this setup a shifted body will be undetermined (no role can eb seen)

*Diseased* - a very not tasty villager, when eaten by wolves they can not take a kill the following night

*Protector* - can protect 1 player at night from being killed, can not protect the same player 2 nights in a row

*Courtesan* - can roleblock 1 player at night

### wolv alligned: ###

*Bloodhound* - can check the exact role of a player at night, can also check the dead, can't take the kill

*Werewolf* - basic wolf 

*Shapeshifter* - a special wolf, that can decide to shift into another players avatar once per game

*Alphawolf* - can take an extra kill once per game (makes it a night with possible 2 deaths)

*Direwolf* - can roleblock a player each night, can't take the kill
